44a735e1-835c-4729-a198-315de8fad988.6198a793-e17b-476f-a4d3-dfefdc155025.description=
Searches for specific properties in LDAP. Returns a list of the values of the given properties for the first object that passes the filter (given in the corresponding input). The rest of the property values (for the other objects) are stored in a collection that is accessible via the LDAP Search Next Result operation.

Input Parameters\:
host - Name or IP address of LDAP server to query. Can also be used in the form " host\:port".
DN - Base DN for search.
filter - Search filter (see Note section).
propertyNames - Names of properties to return (ex. distinguishedName,telephoneNumber).
username - Name of user to connect to LDAP as.
password - Password of user.
port - Specify the port in case it is not the default one, or it is not specified in the host path.
delimiter - A delimiter to separate the property names in the input and the property values in the result. If no value is assigned the delimiter is set to "," by default.

Responses\:
success - was able to retrieve objects and property values from LDAP. First value returned as returnResult result
failure - either no objects were found, an invalid or duplicate property name was provided or an error occured. See returnResult for more information

Note\:
The filter input can be a simple filter, or a composed one. The filter can be composed by the rules described in "RFC2254 - The String Representation of LDAP Search Filters" which can be found at http\://www.faqs.org/rfcs/rfc2254.html.  

Example of valid filters\:
member\=CN\=User1,CN\=Users,DC\=mydomain,DC\=local
(|(numsubordinates\=1)(entryid\=15))
(&(mobile\=*)(name\=abcd))
(&(objectClass\=Person)(|(sn\=Jensen)(cn\=Babs J*)))
44a735e1-835c-4729-a198-315de8fad988.676f3b33-a537-45c3-bd66-cbfa71b83f46.description=

44a735e1-835c-4729-a198-315de8fad988.7757a539-2168-47a2-a7e5-2e6ad74bef64.description=
Searches for specific properties in LDAP. Returns a list of the values of the given properties for the first object that passes the filter (given in the corresponding input). The remaining property values (for the other objects) are stored in a collection that is accessible using the LDAP Search Next Result operation.

Inputs\:
    host - Name or IP address of LDAP server to query. Can also be used in the form " host\:port".
    DN - Base DN for search
    filter - Search filter (see Note below)
    propertyNames - Names of properties to return (for example, distinguishedName,telephoneNumber)
    username - Name of user to be used to connect to LDAP
    password - Password of user
    port - Number of the port (if the port is not default, or not specified in the host path)
    delimiter - A delimiter to separate the property names in the input and the property values in the result. If no value is assigned, the delimiter is set to "," by default.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description. The first value is returned as returnResult result.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully. See returnResult for more information.

Note\:
The filter input can be a simple or composed filter. A composed filter should follow the rules described in "RFC2254 - The String Representation of LDAP Search Filters" located at http\://www.faqs.org/rfcs/rfc2254.html.  

Examples of valid filters\:
member\=CN\=User1,CN\=Users,DC\=mydomain,DC\=local
(|(numsubordinates\=1)(entryid\=15))
(&(mobile\=*)(name\=abcd))
(&(objectClass\=Person)(|(sn\=Jensen)(cn\=Babs J*)))


44a735e1-835c-4729-a198-315de8fad988.986b6183-047b-473c-b07e-94fb673c1c8f.description=
If the input dateFormat is not specified, converts a date in the OO Central Server date/time format dependent on the Java locale, to a date in the OO Central Server date/time format or in the format specified in the input parameter outFormat. 

If the input dateFormat is specified, converts a date in the format in dateFormat to a date either in OO Central Server date/time format or in the format specified in the input outFormat.

You can use flow "Get Current Date and Time" to check upon the default date/time format.  

For example, if OO Central Server's locale is English, the input dateFormat is empty and the input outFormat is empty, the input date should be in the format of "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:08 AM". If the user specifies dateFormat as "dd-MM-YYYY HH\:mm\:ss", the input date should be in the format of "13-07-2006 10\:04\:08". If the input outFormat is empty, the result will be "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:08 AM". If the input outFormat is "yyyy-MM-dd", the result will be "2006-07-13". The dateFormat for "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:078 AM" is "MMM dd, yyyy HH\:mm\:ss a". 


Specify the date format with the following patterns\:

Letter 	Date or Time Component 	Presentation 	Examples
G 	Era designator 	Text 	                     AD
y 	Year 	                     Year 	                     1996; 96
M 	Month in year 	Month 	                     July; Jul; 07
w 	Week in year 	Number 	                     27
W 	Week in month 	Number 	                     2
D 	Day in year 	                     Number 	                     189
d 	Day in month 	Number 	                     10
F 	Day of week in month 	Number 	                     2
E 	Day in week   	Text 	                     Tuesday; Tue
a 	Am/pm marker 	Text 	                     PM
H 	Hour in day (0-23) 	Number 	                     0
k 	Hour in day (1-24) 	Number 	                     24
K 	Hour in am/pm (0-11) 	Number 	                     0
h 	Hour in am/pm (1-12) 	Number 	                     12
m 	Minute in hour 	Number 	                     30
s 	Second in minute 	Number 	                     55
S 	Millisecond 	                     Number 	                     978
z 	Time zone 	                     General time zone 	Pacific Standard Time; PST; GMT-08\:00
Z 	Time zone 	                     RFC 822 time zone 	-0800

For example, the date "2006-07-10 15\:16\:14.766 PDT" would have the dateFormat "yyyy-MM-dd HH\:mm\:ss.SSS z".

You can also use single quotes (') to avoid text interpretation. The quoted text will simply be copied into the output string during formatting (if present in the outFormat) or matched against the input string during parsing (if present in the dateFormat). For example, the date value "2006-07-10T15\:16\:14.766Z" would have the dateFormat "yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSS'Z'". 


Inputs\:
    date - The date to parse. If the input dateFormat is empty, the date must be in the OO Central Server date/time format which is dependent on the Java locale.                        If the input dateFormat is not empty, the date must be in the format specified in  input dateFormat.
    dateFormat - The format of the input date. 
    dateLocaleLang - The locale language for the input dateFormat string. For example,  en or ja.  This will be ignored if dateFormat is empty. 
    dateLocaleCountry - The locale country for the input dateFormat string. For example, US or JP.  This will be ignored if dateFormat is empty or dateLocaleLang is
               empty. 
    outFormat - The  output date/time format. If empty, the output date/time will be in the OO Central Server date/time format, which is dependent on the Java locale.
    outLocaleLang - The locale language for output string. For example,  en or ja. This will be ignored if outFormat is empty. 
    outLocaleCountry - The locale country for output string. For example, US or JP. This will be ignored if outFormat is empty or outLocaleLang is empty.

Responses\:
     success - The operation completed as stated in the description (value is op result)
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully

Result\:
The date in the new format.

44a735e1-835c-4729-a198-315de8fad988.description=
Finds the primary domain controller for a domain via DNS lookup and checks to see if an account is locked.

Inputs\:
    domain - The name of the domain to find the domain controller for (for example, domain.com)
    dnsServer - The DNS server to query (for example, dnsserver.domain.com)
    sAMAccountName - The value of the sAMAccountName attribute of the user whose account is checked
    altuser - The username to use when authenticating with the host (for example, domain/username)
    altpass - The password for altuser

Output\:
    returnResult - A string stating whether or not the account is locked

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully
